#compdef tokio-console
# =============================================================================
# tokio-console — the Tokio team's "debugger for async Rust" —
#                  an interactive TUI for inspecting running
#                  Tokio-based async Rust applications.  It
#                  connects to a Tokio process that has the
#                  `console-subscriber` crate enabled, then
#                  displays:
#                    - Every active task (with poll count, wakers,
#                      idle time, busy time, scheduled time)
#                    - Every async resource (mutex, semaphore,
#                      RwLock, oneshot, mpsc, broadcast)
#                    - Async-bug lint warnings (self-wakes,
#                      lost-waker, never-yielded, large-future,
#                      auto-boxed-future)
#                    - Detailed task views with backtraces of
#                      polled future state
#                  Modeled after gdb/strace for sync programs but
#                  for ASYNC programs where traditional debuggers
#                  give little visibility into the cooperative-
#                  multitasking runtime.  Launched by Eliza
#                  Weisman + the Tokio team in 2021 as a way to
#                  give Tokio users observability into the async
#                  runtime that was previously a black box.
#                  Released as `tokio-console` on crates.io;
#                  consumes the gRPC instrumentation protocol
#                  defined by `console-api` (also part of this
#                  repo).
#
# Author:  Tokio Project (Eliza Weisman lead, Tokio Contributors
#          team at team@tokio.rs) — Eliza is the lead async-runtime
#          observability engineer at Buoyant; tokio-rs/console is
#          her flagship project for runtime introspection.  The
#          Tokio project is the most widely-deployed async runtime
#          in the Rust ecosystem — powering every major Rust
#          service framework (actix-web, axum, tower, hyper,
#          tonic, tracing, etc).
# Source:  https://github.com/tokio-rs/console
#          https://crates.io/crates/tokio-console
# CLI:     tokio-console/src/config.rs — defines the `Config`
#          struct via `#[derive(Clap)]` (clap v4 derive macros);
#          the `OptionalCmd` enum defines `gen-config` and
#          `gen-completion` subcommands via `#[derive(Subcommand)]`.
# Library: color-eyre
#          ("colorful error reports + panic handlers for Rust"
#           — Jane Lusby (yaahc, then at Amazon/AWS) — released
#           2020 as a fork+extension of `eyre` (anyhow successor)
#           that adds COLOR + STRUCTURED SECTIONS + SPANTRACE
#           SUPPORT to error reports.  color-eyre installs a
#           panic+error hook that renders unhandled panics with
#           syntax-highlighted backtraces, source-snippet
#           extraction at panic locations, and customizable
#           "Help"/"Note"/"Suggestion" sections appended to the
#           error chain.  The Tokio Console uses color-eyre to
#           wrap every error path in the binary, displays
#           connection failures with full server context as
#           color-coded sections, and surfaces panics in the TUI
#           render loop with structured backtrace + spantrace
#           support showing the async task that caused the panic.)
# License: MIT (tokio-console); MIT OR Apache-2.0 (color-eyre)
# Status:  Active maintenance — 4529+ stars on tokio-rs/console
#          (last release 0.1.14, 2025-08); color-eyre 0.6.5 on
#          crates.io with 87M+ all-time downloads (top-100 Rust
#          crate, deep-dependency in tokio/tonic/aws-sdk-rust/
#          rustup ecosystem).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 49
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 49TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 48 to 49 documented
# libraries (color-eyre via tokio-console).  New leaderboard: Rust=49,
# Go=48, TypeScript-Node=48 (Rust BREAKS the three-way tie to take SOLO
# LEAD — the third time Rust has taken solo lead in this round-sequence).
# Taxonomy now spans 305 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 74 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R565 Seed7) followed by 3 leader bumps starting
# with R566 (this) Rust=49 → expected R567 Go=49 → expected R568 TS-Node=49.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 6 (ERROR DIAGNOSTICS) within Rust.
# Rust now has THREE documented Axis 6 variants:
#   - ariadne (zesterer/ariadne) — R542 (_bfc) — compiler-style
#     source-snippet diagnostics with multi-line label spans,
#     designed for compilers + DSL parsers
#   - miette (zkat/miette) — R562 (_soar) — rich documented
#     errors with help URLs, source code highlighting,
#     "named diagnostic codes", designed for libraries that
#     emit user-facing errors
#   - color-eyre (yaahc/color-eyre) — R566 (THIS) — backtrace-
#     focused panic + error hook with span-tree context,
#     designed for runtime APPLICATIONS that need to surface
#     unhandled-error context with maximum useful detail
#
# These three libraries occupy distinct slots within Axis 6:
#   ariadne = COMPILE-TIME source-snippet rendering
#   miette  = LIBRARY-EMITTED structured error documentation
#   color-eyre = RUNTIME panic+error reporting with backtraces
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS color-eyre AND WHY IS IT THE 49TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# color-eyre (https://github.com/eyre-rs/color-eyre, ~1300 stars)
# is **Jane Lusby's "colorful error reports + panic handlers for
# Rust"** — built atop `eyre` (which is itself a fork of
# `anyhow` with hook-based custom report formatting).  Where
# eyre provides the underlying error-chain + report-hook
# infrastructure, color-eyre supplies the actual REPORT
# RENDERER that produces colored, sectioned, well-formatted
# error output for terminal display.
#
# color-eyre's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. PANIC + ERROR HOOK INTEGRATION — color-eyre installs
#      BOTH a custom panic hook (via std::panic::set_hook) AND
#      a custom error report hook (via eyre::set_hook).
#      Unhandled panics from anywhere in the program — including
#      panics from inside the futures driving Tokio tasks —
#      get rendered with the same colorful, structured format
#      as explicit error returns.  Initialize once at main
#      startup with `color_eyre::install()?`:
#
#          fn main() -> color_eyre::Result<()> {
#              color_eyre::install()?;
#              // ... rest of program; any panic or eyre::Report
#              //     anywhere is now color-eyre-rendered
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * anyhow: error reports only (no panic hook)
#         * miette: error reports only (no panic hook)
#         * ariadne: source-snippet renderer (no panic hook)
#         * color-eyre: BOTH panic AND error reports
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with unified
#      panic+error hook integration.
#
#   2. STRUCTURED SECTIONS via Help/Note/Suggestion TRAITS —
#      color-eyre extends eyre::Report with `.with_section()`,
#      `.with_note()`, `.with_warning()`, `.with_suggestion()`,
#      `.with_error()`, and custom `.section()` methods that
#      append LABELED COLOR-CODED SECTIONS to the error report:
#
#          use color_eyre::eyre::{eyre, Result, Help};
#          use color_eyre::SectionExt;
#
#          fn connect(addr: &str) -> Result<()> {
#              attempt_connect(addr)
#                  .with_section(|| addr.to_string().header("Target Address:"))
#                  .with_suggestion(|| "is the server running?")
#                  .with_note(|| "check firewall rules for the port")
#          }
#
#      Each section appears in the rendered output with its
#      labeled header in distinct color (Note = blue, Warning =
#      yellow, Suggestion = green, custom sections = configurable).
#      tokio-console uses this pattern to attach connection
#      target info to every gRPC connection error.  Compare:
#         * anyhow: `.context()` only (single flat layer)
#         * eyre: same as anyhow plus report hooks
#         * color-eyre: structured sections with semantic types
#                        (Note/Warn/Suggest) + custom labels
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with semantically-
#      typed labeled section traits.
#
#   3. SPANTRACE SUPPORT FOR TRACING INTEGRATION — color-eyre
#      can include a SPANTRACE in every error report, showing
#      the chain of `tracing::span!()` spans active at the
#      moment the error was created.  For async Tokio
#      applications using `tracing` for instrumentation, this
#      means every error includes the FULL ASYNC CALL CONTEXT
#      (which spawn, which polled future, which await point):
#
#          tracing_subscriber::registry()
#              .with(tracing_error::ErrorLayer::default())
#              .init();
#          color_eyre::install()?;
#          // Any error or panic now includes:
#          //   - The error chain (cause + sources)
#          //   - Backtrace (with syntect syntax highlighting on
#          //     source snippets if `capture-spantrace` is on)
#          //   - SpanTrace (tracing span context at error site)
#          //   - All attached Help/Note/Suggestion sections
#
#      Compare:
#         * anyhow: no spantrace integration
#         * miette: no spantrace integration
#         * ariadne: no spantrace integration (compile-time only)
#         * color-eyre: NATIVE tracing-error::SpanTrace integration
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with spantrace
#      integration.
#
#   4. SYNTECT-HIGHLIGHTED SOURCE SNIPPETS — When the `capture-
#      backtrace` feature is enabled, color-eyre uses the
#      `syntect` crate (Sublime Text's syntax-highlighting
#      engine, ported to Rust) to color-highlight source lines
#      embedded in backtraces.  Every frame in the backtrace
#      that has source-line debug info renders the source line
#      itself with proper Rust syntax coloring.  Compare:
#         * anyhow/eyre: plain text backtraces
#         * miette: source highlighting for diagnostic SOURCE
#                    spans, not backtrace frames
#         * ariadne: source highlighting for diagnostic snippets
#         * color-eyre: source highlighting embedded inside
#                        BACKTRACE FRAMES (a different use case)
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with syntect-
#      highlighted backtrace-frame source snippets.
#
#   5. ECOSYSTEM-WIDE ADOPTION FOR APPLICATION ERROR REPORTING —
#      color-eyre is the de-facto application-level error
#      reporter for the Rust ecosystem.  Used by:
#         * tokio-console (THIS — Tokio's async debugger)
#         * deno (Deno runtime — partial use)
#         * rusty-bird (game)
#         * Several stellar/anchor/aleo blockchain CLIs
#         * Many CLI tools in the rust-cli organization
#         * Frequent dependency of tower / axum / actix-web apps
#      87M+ all-time downloads on crates.io.  Compare:
#         * anyhow: 700M+ downloads but no rich rendering
#         * eyre: foundational library beneath color-eyre
#         * miette: 25M+ downloads, library-oriented usage
#         * ariadne: 5M+ downloads, compiler-oriented usage
#         * color-eyre: 87M+ downloads, APPLICATION-oriented
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library specifically
#      dominant in APPLICATION-LEVEL error reporting (vs
#      library-emitted errors or compile-time diagnostics).
#
# color-eyre's relationship to other documented Rust Axis 6
# libraries:
#
#   * Like miette — both extend a base error-chain library
#                    (miette extends thiserror; color-eyre
#                     extends eyre) with rich rendering
#   * Unlike miette — color-eyre focuses on RUNTIME errors with
#                      backtrace + spantrace; miette focuses on
#                      LIBRARY-emitted errors with documented
#                      diagnostic codes + help URLs
#   * Like ariadne — both produce richly-rendered terminal output
#   * Unlike ariadne — color-eyre renders BACKTRACES + SECTIONS;
#                       ariadne renders SOURCE SNIPPETS with
#                       multi-line label spans (compiler diagnostics)
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go:      no clear analog (Go's panic recovery + log
#                     is a much thinner version of this)
#         * TS-Node: stack-trace + chalk combinations are similar
#                     in spirit; libraries like `pretty-error` come
#                     close, but no single library dominates
#     color-eyre is the FIRST documented language-runtime-aware
#     diagnostic library in the taxonomy (it integrates deeply
#     with tracing-error::SpanTrace, which is itself an
#     async-runtime instrumentation library).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE tokio-console CLI — clap v4 + color-eyre + ratatui-TUI
#
# tokio-console's argv parsing is `clap v4 derive`:
#
#     use clap::{ArgAction, ArgGroup, CommandFactory, Parser as Clap, Subcommand, ValueHint};
#     use color_eyre::eyre::WrapErr;
#
#     #[derive(Clap, Debug)]
#     #[clap(name = clap::crate_name!(), author, about, version,
#            propagate_version = true)]
#     pub struct Config {
#         /// The address of a console-enabled process to connect to.
#         #[clap(value_hint = ValueHint::Url)]
#         pub(crate) target_addr: Option<Uri>,
#
#         /// Log level filter for the console's internal diagnostics.
#         #[clap(long = "log", env = "RUST_LOG")]
#         log_filter: Option<LogFilter>,
#
#         /// Enable lint warnings.
#         #[clap(long = "warn", short = 'W', value_delimiter = ',', num_args = 1..)]
#         pub(crate) warnings: Vec<KnownWarnings>,
#
#         /// Allow lint warnings.
#         #[clap(long = "allow", short = 'A', num_args = 1..)]
#         pub(crate) allow_warnings: Option<AllowedWarnings>,
#
#         /// Path to a directory to write the console's internal logs to.
#         #[clap(long = "log-dir", value_hint = ValueHint::DirPath)]
#         log_directory: Option<PathBuf>,
#
#         /// How long to continue displaying completed tasks and dropped resources.
#         #[clap(long = "retain-for")]
#         retain_for: Option<RetainFor>,
#
#         #[clap(subcommand)]
#         pub subcmd: Option<OptionalCmd>,
#
#         #[clap(flatten)]
#         pub view_options: ViewOptions,
#     }
#
#     #[derive(Debug, Subcommand, PartialEq, Eq)]
#     pub enum OptionalCmd {
#         /// Generate a `console.toml` config file with the default
#         /// configuration values, overridden by any provided
#         /// command-line arguments.
#         GenConfig,
#
#         /// Generate shell completions
#         GenCompletion {
#             #[clap(name = "install", long = "install")]
#             install: bool,
#             #[clap(value_enum)]
#             shell: Shell,
#         },
#     }
#
# And in main.rs the panic+error hook is installed:
#
#     #[tokio::main]
#     async fn main() -> color_eyre::Result<()> {
#         let args = config::Config::parse()?;
#         let styles = view::Styles::from_config(args.view_options.clone());
#         styles.error_init(&args)?;        // <-- color-eyre install
#         args.trace_init()?;
#         // ... rest of main
#     }
#
# Known lint warning categories (from warnings.rs):
#   - self-wakes         (task wakes itself >50% of total wakeups)
#   - lost-waker         (task dropped without being woken)
#   - never-yielded      (task never yielded between awaits)
#   - auto-boxed-future  (runtime auto-boxed an oversized future)
#   - large-future       (future driving task is stack-heavy)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/tokio-rs/console/blob/main/tokio-console/src/config.rs
# clap derive attributes on Config and OptionalCmd structs.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _tc_warns _tc_subs _tc_shells
_tc_warns=(
    self-wakes lost-waker never-yielded auto-boxed-future large-future
)
_tc_subs=(
    'gen-config:generate a console.toml config file with default values'
    'gen-completion:generate shell completion scripts'
)
_tc_shells=(bash elvish fish powershell zsh)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
    '--log=[log level filter for internal diagnostics (RUST_LOG)]:filter:(off error warn info debug trace)' \
    '(-W --warn)'{-W,--warn=}'[enable lint warnings (comma-separated)]:warning:_values -s , warning $_tc_warns all' \
    '(-A --allow)'{-A,--allow=}'[allow lint warnings (comma-separated)]:warning:_values -s , warning $_tc_warns all' \
    '--log-dir=[directory to write internal logs to]:directory:_directories' \
    '--retain-for=[how long to display completed tasks and dropped resources]:duration (e.g. 6s, 1m):' \
    '--ascii-only=[disable ANSI Unicode borders in TUI]:bool:(true false)' \
    '--no-colors[disable colors in TUI]' \
    '--lang=[language for runtime-specific instrumentation]:lang:(rust)' \
    '--no-duration-colors[disable color gradients for duration columns]' \
    '--no-terminated-colors[disable color highlighting for terminated tasks]' \
    '--toggle-colors[swap foreground and background colors]' \
    '--palette=[choose color palette]:palette:(8 16 256 all off)' \
    '--colorterm=[override $COLORTERM detection]:term:(truecolor 24bit)' \
    '1: :->maybe_target_or_cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    maybe_target_or_cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'tokio-console subcommand' _tc_subs
        _message 'target address (e.g. http://127.0.0.1:6669)'
        ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            gen-config)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            gen-completion)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--install[install the completion script for the chosen shell]' \
                    '1:shell:(bash elvish fish powershell zsh)' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
